%S A393125 0,16,16,16,16,416,16
%N A393125 Maximum of the orbit of n under the map x -> 5x+1 if odd else x/2; -1 if the orbit is unbounded.
%C A393125 It is conjectured but still unproven that a(7) = -1.
%C A393125 Only three cycles are known for the map x -> (5x+1 if odd else x/2):
%C A393125   A: [1 -> 6 -> 3 -> 16 -> 8 -> 4 -> 2 -> 1],
%C A393125   B: [13 -> 66 -> 33 -> 166 -> 83 -> 416 -> 208 -> 104 -> 52 -> 26 -> 13],
%C A393125   C: [17 -> 86 -> 43 -> 216 -> 108 -> 54 -> 27 -> 136 -> 68 -> 34 -> 17].
%C A393125 Obviously, if x is a member of one of these, then any number of the form x*2^k will end in this cycle, but others can do so, too; for example, 5 -> 26 -> B.
%C A393125 The trajectory of most larger odd numbers appears to grow infinitely. For example, the orbit of 11 comprises 7 and 9 and then keeps growing, cf. A259193.
%C A393125 We mention that there is a different "5x+1" map, which divides not only by 2 but also by 3 if possible, see for example A057688.
%H A393125 M. F. Hasler, <a href="/A393125/a393125_1.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0 .. 1000, with "?" if the orbit has elements larger than n*10^9</a>, where conjecturally a(n) = -1.
%H A393125 Alex V. Kontorovich and Jeffrey C. Lagarias, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/0910.1944">Stochastic Models for the 3x+1 and 5x+1 Problems</a>, arXiv:0910.1944 [math.NT], 2009.
%H A393125 Robert Soupe, <a href="https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/1350893">Does the 5x+1 sequence for 7 reach a power of 2 or does it get stuck in a period?</a>, on math.StackExchange, Jul 06 2015.
%F A393125 a(n*2^k) = max(a(n), n*2^k), with -1 representing oo.
%e A393125 The orbits of the first initial values are:
%e A393125  n = 0 -> 0 -> ..., so a(0) = 0
%e A393125  n = 1 -> 6 -> 3 -> 16 -> 8 -> 4 -> 2 -> 1 -> ..., so a(1) = 16
%e A393125  n = 2 -> 1 -> 6 -> 3 -> 16 -> 8 -> 4 -> 2 -> ..., so a(2) = 16
%e A393125  n = 3 -> 16 -> 8 -> 4 -> 2 -> 1 -> 6 -> 3 -> ..., so a(3) = 16
%e A393125  n = 4 -> 2 -> 1 -> 6 -> 3 -> 16 -> 8 -> 4 -> ..., so a(4) = 16
%e A393125  n = 5 -> 26 -> 13 -> 66 -> 33 -> 166 -> 83 -> 416 -> 208 -> 104 -> 52 -> 26 -> ..., so a(5) = 416
%e A393125  n = 6 -> 3 -> 16 -> 8 -> 4 -> 2 -> 1 -> 6 -> ..., so a(4) = 16
%e A393125  n = 7 -> 36 -> 18 -> 9 -> 46 -> 23 -> 116 -> 58 -> 29 -> 146 -> 73 -> 366 -> 183 -> 916 -> 458 -> 229 -> 1146 -> 573 -> 2866 -> 1433 -> ...: see A028389.
%e A393125  n = 640 -> 320 -> ... -> 5 -> ... is the least starting value larger than the maximum of the limiting cycle.
%e A393125 More unknown entries (conjectured to be -1) are n = 7, 9, 11, 14, 18, 21..23, 25, 28, 29, 31, 35..37, 39, 41, 42, 44..47, 49, 50, ... (see linked a-file). For any n in that list, all n*2^k are of course also in this list, cf. formula.
%o A393125 (PARI) apply( {A393125(n,oo=n<<30)=my(m=n, M=n, L=n); until(setsearch([m,L,M], n=if(n%2, 5*n+1, n\2)), if(n>M, (oo<M=n) && return("?"), n<m, L=m=n, n>L, L=n)); M}, [0..60]) \\ The "?" stand for orbits with values larger than the 2nd optional parameter, by default n*2^30 ~ n*10^9, where conjecturally a(n) = -1. If oo is given as 2nd parameter, the function might never return.
%Y A393125 Cf. A028389 (trajectory of 7), A259207 (trajectory of 5), A259193 (trajectory of 11).
%Y A393125 Cf. A057688 (trajectory of 5 under a different 5x+1 map: use x/3 if integer).
